      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this lesson on AI in everyday tools. Now, when most people think about artificial intelligence, they imagine something futuristic or complicated, something they have consciously chosen to use. But here is the thing: AI is already woven into the tools you use every single day, and most of the time, it is not signposted at all. Your email client, your search engine, your spreadsheet software, even your smartphone keyboard, all of these have AI quietly working away in the background. There is no big announcement, no flashing label saying \"AI is here.\" It is simply built in. And because it feels so familiar and ordinary, most of us do not stop to think about what that actually means. The risks that come with using AI-powered tools often go completely unnoticed, precisely because we do not realise we are using AI in the first place. That is exactly what we are going to explore together in this lesson."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "Let's start by looking at where AI is already showing up in the tools you probably use every single day, often without you even realising it. When you open your email and a suggested reply appears at the bottom of the screen, that is AI. When your word processor quietly fixes a spelling mistake or finishes a sentence for you, that is AI as well. Even in something as familiar as a spreadsheet, you might notice it offering to complete a pattern or suggest a formula. Type something into a search bar and watch it predict what you are about to ask, again, that is AI working behind the scenes. And if you have ever been in an online meeting where a transcript appeared automatically, yes, AI was listening and converting speech to text in real time. The point here is that AI is not some distant, futuristic technology. It is already woven into the everyday tools sitting right in front of you."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "Here is the narration script for Slide 3:\n\nSo here is something that catches a lot of people off guard. The tools you use every single day, your email, your grammar checker, your calendar app, they often have AI built in, and that AI is quietly doing quite a lot behind the scenes. When your email suggests how to finish a sentence, those words may be travelling to an external server somewhere. When you use a grammar or writing tool, it is quite likely storing and analysing everything you type, not just checking your spelling. And many productivity apps will share your documents with third-party AI systems without making that particularly obvious to you. Perhaps most surprising is your smart scheduling assistant. To work properly, it may be reading your calendar, your contacts, and your meeting notes. None of this is necessarily malicious, but the key point is that most of these features are switched on by default. You have not necessarily agreed to any of it consciously, and that is worth paying attention to."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "Here is the narration script for Slide 4:\n\nLet's talk about something that catches a lot of people off guard. Those helpful little features built into your everyday tools, the ones that finish your sentences, fix your grammar, or suggest a meeting time, they are not just running quietly on your device. In many cases, they are sending your data to external servers to do their work. Your email client might be reading fragments of what you type before you even hit send. Your grammar checker could be storing a copy of your document in the cloud. Your smart scheduling assistant might have access to your entire calendar and contact list. And here is the part that really matters: most of these features are switched on by default. You did not choose them, you were simply opted in. So the question is not whether these tools are useful, because they genuinely are. The question is whether you know what they are doing in the background."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Here is the narration script for Slide 5:\n\nThose helpful little suggestions that pop up when you are typing an email or working in a spreadsheet? They are not magic. Behind the scenes, many of these tools are sending what you type to external servers just to generate that suggestion. Your actual words, from real documents and real emails, are being processed somewhere else entirely. And with free productivity tools especially, it is worth asking: if you are not paying for the product, how is it being funded? Often, the answer is your data. Some of these smart features are quietly logging what you type before you even press send, and that information can feed into the very AI models being trained by the companies behind these tools. So the convenience is real, but so is the cost. It is just not a cost you see on an invoice. Being aware of this is the first step towards making more informed choices about the tools you use every day."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "Let's take a moment to look at where AI is already showing up in the tools you probably use every single day. When you open Outlook or Gmail and a suggested reply pops up, that's AI. When your spell checker does more than fix a typo and actually rewrites a sentence to sound more formal or friendly, that's AI too, and it's often switched on without you realising. The same goes for tools like PowerPoint or Canva, which quietly suggest layouts and images as you build a presentation. Your calendar app may be analysing your working patterns to recommend meeting times, and even the search bar on your company's internal systems might be using AI to decide which results appear at the top. None of this requires you to do anything special to activate it. It's already there, already influencing your work. The first step is simply knowing where to look."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So now that we understand where AI is hiding in our everyday tools, let's talk about what you can actually do to reduce your exposure. First, it's worth spending a few minutes going into the privacy settings of the apps you use regularly and checking what's switched on by default. You might be surprised. If there are AI features you simply don't need or use, turn them off. There's no reason to leave them running in the background. Be mindful about the information you type into any tool, especially anything sensitive like client details or confidential business data. When an app sends you an update notice, don't just click through it. Take a moment to read what's changed, because AI features are often quietly added in updates. And finally, wherever possible, stick to the software your organisation has officially approved. Those tools are far more likely to have been reviewed with your security and privacy in mind."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring everything together with a few key points worth holding onto. First, AI is not always obvious. It's quietly built into the tools you already use every day, so you may be using it without even realising. Second, when you use those tools, your data could be going somewhere, so it's worth being mindful of what you're sharing and with whom. Make a habit of checking your privacy settings from time to time, because they can change, and it's easy to miss an update. Before you type anything sensitive into a tool, just pause for a moment and ask yourself whether that information should really be going into an AI-powered system. And finally, you don't have to figure all of this out on your own. Your IT team is there to help, so please do reach out to them with any questions or concerns. These are simple habits, but they can make a real difference."
        }
      ]
